Okay, I will help you fix the "Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'avatar')" error.

Here's the plan:

1.  **Identify the root cause:** The error indicates that the `avatar` property is being accessed on a `user` object that is sometimes undefined. This likely happens in `PostCard.tsx` or similar components where user data is displayed.
2.  **Implement a fix:** Implement a conditional check to ensure that the `user` object exists before accessing the `avatar` property.

Here's what you need to do:

```typescript
// components/PostCard.tsx
const PostCard = ({ post }) => {
  return (
    <View>
      {post.user && post.user.avatar ? (
        <Image source={{ uri: post.user.avatar }} />
      ) : (
        <Text>No Avatar</Text> // Or a default avatar
      )}
      <Text>{post.user?.username}</Text>
      {/* ... other post details */}
    </View>
  );
};
```

This code adds a check to ensure that `post.user` exists and that `post.user.avatar` exists before attempting to render the image. If either of these is undefined, it will render "No Avatar" text instead (you can replace this with a default avatar image if you prefer). I also added optional chaining for the username in case the user object is null.

